{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621673"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:57:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:57:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16770"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16770"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.13,0.79,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66875"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9461"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16770"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52329"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5016"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22356"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22358"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66875"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThrombolytic therapy is an important treatment option for acute thrombotic conditions such as myocardial infarction and ischaemic stroke.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of tissue plasminogen activator?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents fibrinogen conversion to fibrin","Directly breaks down fibrin clots","Converts plasminogen to plasmin","Inhibits platelet aggregation","Blocks vitamin K-dependent clotting factors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETissue plasminogen activator (tPA) works by \u003Cstrong\u003Econverting plasminogen to plasmin\u003C/strong\u003E. Plasmin is the active enzyme that breaks down fibrin clots. tPA has high specificity for fibrin-bound plasminogen, making it an effective targeted thrombolytic agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly breaking down fibrin clots\u003C/strong\u003E is not how tPA works - it requires the intermediate step of plasmin activation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting platelet aggregation\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of antiplatelet medications such as aspirin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreventing fibrinogen conversion to fibrin\u003C/strong\u003E describes how heparin works through antithrombin III. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking vitamin K-dependent clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fibrin specificity of tPA means it primarily acts at sites of clot formation, reducing systemic effects. This makes it particularly useful in acute situations requiring rapid clot dissolution.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) converts plasminogen to plasmin, which breaks down fibrin clots.","tPA is highly specific for fibrin-bound plasminogen, making it effective for targeted clot dissolution.","tPA is used clinically for treating acute myocardial infarction and ischaemic stroke within specific time windows."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52329"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16770"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52329"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T07:32:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T07:32:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9461"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66875"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":